Problem 0: some fake data to mess with¶

First, let's make a time axis that goes from 0 to 100 π in 1e5 steps

In [2]:
t = np.linspace(0,np.pi*100,int(1e5))

Then an offset sinusoid

In [3]:
N = 10+np.sin(t)

Then some random background data whose mean and variance depend on N

In [4]:
bkgd = stats.norm.rvs(size=int(1e5))*np.sqrt(N)+N

Problem 2: density¶

Plotting a scatter plot of 100,000 points can get very messy, especially in the central areas where the points all overlap. So instead, we can plot the density of points using a 2D histogram

2a) Make a 2D histogram plot

In [8]:
plt.hist2d(t, bkgd, bins=75)
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Background')
plt.colorbar()
Out[8]:
<matplotlib.colorbar.Colorbar at 0x7f7bb5269e20>

2b) Clearly explain what is being plotted in your plot (e.g. what does each color mean?)

Instead of plotting each individual points, we are plotting a density of the data points in some given bins. The colors are bins (densities) they the color bar on the right indicates how many plots are in each bins corresponding to the colors.

Problem 3: Folding¶

If we have a periodic signal, it is possible to fold the data stream at that period to make the pattern clearer.

3a) Make an new time variable that folds at a period of 2π (the modulo operator is your friend, variably expressed as mod(), %, or rem()). Then make a scatter plot of all your data, but now folded. (Reminder, for more data you'd never actually want to plot all the points.)

In [9]:
folded_time = t % 2*np.pi



start = int(len(folded_time)/4)
end = int(len(folded_time)/2) + start

colors = np.random.rand(len(folded_time[start:end:step]))
plt.scatter(folded_time[start:end:step], bkgd[start:end:step], c=colors)
plt.xlabel('Folded Time')
plt.ylabel('Fake Fake')
plt.plot()
